01:01:55.140 --> 01:02:02.380
&gt;&gt;male #1: You contrasted the methodologies
of the corporate cultures between the NASA

01:02:02.380 --> 01:02:03.380
--

01:02:03.380 --> 01:02:04.380
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:02:04.380 --> 01:02:08.010
&gt;&gt;male #1: contractor system and the Playtex
company's school of hard knocks.

01:02:08.010 --> 01:02:09.010
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:02:09.010 --> 01:02:12.940
&gt;&gt;male #1: How far would you push that difference?
Were they just different cultures or were

01:02:12.940 --> 01:02:18.190
they really a contrast between the systemic
method of invention and development versus

01:02:18.190 --> 01:02:21.251
the sort of anarchy kind of --

01:02:21.251 --> 01:02:22.251
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:02:22.251 --> 01:02:23.251
&gt;&gt;male #1: individuals? How far would you
--

01:02:23.251 --> 01:02:27.670
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: It was a massive conflict
and it was not, it was a problematic conflict

01:02:27.670 --> 01:02:33.540
too because Playtex had a huge difficulty
with all the reporting mechanisms, the reliability

01:02:33.540 --> 01:02:38.200
indices, everything that needed to be part
of something like Apollo. And I wouldn't single

01:02:38.200 --> 01:02:44.780
out any one contract in particular but the
whole history of the kind of military industrial

01:02:44.780 --> 01:02:49.870
spacesuit design is full of things like for
instance a double bladder. It looks on paper

01:02:49.870 --> 01:02:53.359
like the most, like it's gonna be the best
solution because you have, all of a sudden

01:02:53.359 --> 01:02:58.130
you have nine nines reliability because the
change of two bladders breaking is so much

01:02:58.130 --> 01:03:04.619
less than one bladder breaking. But then you
also reduce the astronaut to total immobility.

01:03:04.619 --> 01:03:09.750
And the Soviets did this with their first
EVA spacesuit that Leonov wore when he became

01:03:09.750 --> 01:03:15.050
the first man to walk out in space protected
only by a spacesuit. And the spacesuit became,

01:03:15.050 --> 01:03:19.110
this double-aired spacesuit became so immobile
that in the end he needed to let air out of

01:03:19.110 --> 01:03:23.480
it by hand in order to make his way back into
the capsule.

01:03:23.480 --> 01:03:31.560
But the Ames suits and the Litton suits, there
is this, as an architect I design environments

01:03:31.560 --> 01:03:36.040
for people all the time and there's always
a difference between the logic of how something

01:03:36.040 --> 01:03:40.670
works on paper, the logic how an office building
is supposed to make you all work and how the

01:03:40.670 --> 01:03:48.080
office actually works, and how a power plant
actually works and what actually happens.

01:03:48.080 --> 01:03:52.670
And there's always this difference and we're
always in some ways designing for people,

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:57.609
designing for human environments is always
a process of managing this gap.

01:03:57.609 --> 01:04:02.200
But it was particularly because it was in
the nature of the space race that the logic,

01:04:02.200 --> 01:04:06.150
this seemingly invincible systems logic that
had made these incredible objects in terms

01:04:06.150 --> 01:04:15.650
of ICBM's was a logic which had been developed
only in a kind of closed world of these technological

01:04:15.650 --> 01:04:21.890
devices in which it worked very well but not
that had a fundamental difficulty when it

01:04:21.890 --> 01:04:26.500
came to human environments. And that's why
I'm so interested also in all the urban proposals

01:04:26.500 --> 01:04:30.810
that came out of the space race and in their
problems and difficulties which I see as all

01:04:30.810 --> 01:04:34.600
the same piece with the problems and difficulties
that the same companies had designing for

01:04:34.600 --> 01:04:36.030
the human body.

01:04:36.030 --> 01:04:38.180
That make sense?

01:04:38.180 --> 01:04:40.320
&gt;&gt;male #1: Um-hum.

