01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:46.619
&gt;&gt;male #2: So when you speak about the differences
in culture --

01:04:46.619 --> 01:04:47.619
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:04:47.619 --> 01:04:49.050
&gt;&gt;male #2: in these two companies I mean we're
talking about the 60s.

01:04:49.050 --> 01:04:50.050
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:04:50.050 --> 01:04:56.690
&gt;&gt;male #2: I mean for your own experience
can you tell is there similar tensions in

01:04:56.690 --> 01:04:58.890
today's companies? I mean is there --

01:04:58.890 --> 01:04:59.890
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Well I mean I have
--

01:04:59.890 --> 01:05:01.660
&gt;&gt;male #2: Are there lessons that were learned
--

01:05:01.660 --> 01:05:02.660
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Yeah.

01:05:02.660 --> 01:05:04.750
&gt;&gt;male #2: and are actually like have been
applied?

01:05:04.750 --> 01:05:10.790
&gt;&gt;Nicholas de Monchaux: Well, I think it's
really interesting in the context of to be

01:05:10.790 --> 01:05:14.970
talking about this here in Silicon Valley
because of course every Silicon Valley company

01:05:14.970 --> 01:05:21.980
whether it's HP or Apple or Google starts
with a hack in a garage right? That's the

01:05:21.980 --> 01:05:28.460
founding mythology. And so you have I think
especially embedded in the DNA of every technology

01:05:28.460 --> 01:05:34.120
company is a conflict between these enterprises.
At some level it can't stay the same as things

01:05:34.120 --> 01:05:38.890
change from being a hack in a garage to being
a massive company with all kinds of issues

01:05:38.890 --> 01:05:42.650
of liability and accountability, etcetera,
etcetera.

01:05:42.650 --> 01:05:49.300
And it can seem though sometimes in managing
this conflict like the kind of, that you can

01:05:49.300 --> 01:05:54.241
draw a diagram always and this is the problem
that all of us has of designers is that we

01:05:54.241 --> 01:06:00.970
mistake a simulation; whether it's a diagram
on a piece of paper or a complex fluid dynamic

01:06:00.970 --> 01:06:08.600
model, we mistake the kind of seeming legibility
of something that tells us it will work for

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:13.660
something that actually does work. And the
reality of making things work is always a

01:06:13.660 --> 01:06:14.670
balance between the two.

01:06:14.670 --> 01:06:19.270
So to the extent that a company like Hamilton
Standard succeeded it was in its own way through

01:06:19.270 --> 01:06:27.840
managing that conflict. ILC was particularly
good at the practical, the kind of boots on

01:06:27.840 --> 01:06:33.740
the ground level of hacks and the kind working
all this together and it was particularly

01:06:33.740 --> 01:06:37.320
bad at everything else. I mean you see that
in the paperwork all through. It's not like

01:06:37.320 --> 01:06:43.359
in 1965 they suddenly learned how to interact
with NASA. They had a terrible time. If you

01:06:43.359 --> 01:06:48.030
through the weekly memos and things like that
they were always being abraded and censured

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:53.000
and they hadn't adequately reported this and
they hadn't adequately reported that. I don't

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:58.350
mean necessarily even to idealize them as
a company 'cause they had a lot of difficulty

01:06:58.350 --> 01:07:02.600
but they did one thing really, really well
which was understand on a very intimate scale

01:07:02.600 --> 01:07:08.750
how the human body really worked. And they
also to their great credit did manage through

01:07:08.750 --> 01:07:13.380
appropriating personnel and systems from other
military contractors to in the end make it

01:07:13.380 --> 01:07:20.270
all the way through Apollo and engage robustly
with this larger military industrial system.

